title: Grateful Dead Live at Los Angeles Coliseum on 1991-06-01
lineage: Cassette Master (Nakamichi CR-7A) > Tascam DA-3000 (DSF 1-bit/5.8 MHz) >KORG AudioGate 4 > Samplitude Pro X3 Suite > FLAC/24
description:
Set 1

Shakedown Street, Walkin' Blues, Bertha-> Greatest Story Ever Told, Candyman, Queen Jane Approximately, Deal

Set 2

Picasso Moon, Foolish Heart, Playin' In The Band-> Uncle John's Band-> Drums-> Jam-> I Need A Miracle-> Black Peter-> Throwing Stones-> Not Fade Away, E: One More Saturday Night

reviews.review_text:
Only LA Stadium Show Hey All-

Welp, this show was a funny one.  I definitely had a great time, as I was with one of my favorite buds to hang with: Bret Haller. In ‘86 after some Heads got ahold of that batch of Bettyboards, Bret gave me a crispy copy of 5/8/77 and so there’s that.  Supplied me with so much quality music.  Friends with early GD taper Bob Menke among many others and in those days, having a human—not an internet-connection was the only way to get the goods.  
So, I’m already rambling.  ;)  

The Shakedown opener was pretty damn great.  I remember during the main jam Jerry turned to his rig and dealing with something in the mix; you’ll hear him drop out of the mix for a minute or so.  But damn, this sounds so much better than what I remember; there were definitely issues with PA sound for the first set as they’d never played the Coliseum (and never would again).  That said plenty of ripping JG on either side of the equipment issues.  

One thing that was no so cool to see was a huge rush of people trying to get onto the field level of the Coliseum and Bret and I were simply hoping no one got hurt or crushed to death. The rest of the set rolled along with a rare—and hot—midset Bertha > Greatest Story.  Set I absolutely uncorks with a RAGING 10 minute+ Deal to close.  (Deal fans should also check JGB 5/19/89 Irvine for another awesome version. Another 10 minutes of the whole band letting loose).  

Now, I will say that Picasso Moon was exactly what the doctor DIDN’T order for me.  We were hoping for a Scarlet > Fire but….denied.  I will sayI liked the musical figure and arrangement but let’s say I never warmed to the lyrics or the “oooo eeee” vocal.  Derivative Hell in a Bucket bitch/goddess lyrics (though I generally love Barlow’s writing and got to tell him so in Ken Kesey’s living room…..as Ken lit a fat J but that’s another story).  

The Foolish Heart after Picasso was strong and segued into a most welcome and long Playin’. The jam explored some nice themes and eventually melded (for ‘89-‘93) unsurprisingly into UJB which was also nicely jammed both during and after the Dm jam out of the final chorus.  

Rhythm Devils > Space were par for the era and a well-played, if predictable combo of Miracle > Peter > TStones > NFA was fine with both Peter and Not Fade really showing some sparks.  

The Saturday Night encore could’ve been seen from a mile away but no one can really complain about the song.  

Fun time!  Definitely check the Shakedown, Deal and the second set.  The sbd audio for the whole show (without gaps) us up on YT.  Enjoy! 

Eric
